==English==

===Pronunciation===
''Stressed on the second syllable''
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ðɛəˈfɔː/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"DE@fO:/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/ðɛɹˈfɔɹ/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"DErfOr/}}
* {{homophones|therefore}} (first syllable stressed)

===Etymology===
[[there]] + [[for]]

===Adverb===
{{head|en|adverb}}

# [[therefore|Therefore]]: for that or this; for it.
#* '''1892''', [[w:Benjamin Harrison|Benjamin Harrison]], ''[[wikisource:Benjamin Harrison's Fourth State of the Union Address|Fourth State of the Union Address]]''
#*: During the last fiscal year the Secretary purchased ... 54,355,748 ounces of silver and issued in payment '''therefor''' $51,106,608 in notes.

====Usage notes====
* This form of this word is now most commonly used in law.

